"The Azores Archipelago is a magnet for life. It really is a magical place. Launching the Azores as Hope Spot is so logical – just ask the whales. They know how special this place is. This used to be a place where whales were killed and now people are making a living by respecting the whales and having people come out and visit them as fellow citizens of the planet." #SylviaEarle 

The Azores Archipelago was recently recognized as a Hope Spot in support of the comprehensive network of marine protected areas and collaborative efforts to manage and preserve its ecological and biological wonders. 

Splash into this Hope Spot through the link in our bio! 

Hope Spot Champions: Christopher Kim Pham with with Instituto de Investigação em Ciências do Mar Okeanos, Universidade dos Açores and Carla Damaso with OMA - Observatório do Mar dos Açores

Hope Spot Partners: @waittinstitute @oceanoazulfoundation, Azores Marine Litter Lab, Okeanos Research Centre/University of the Azores, @fabricadabaleia, OMA - Observatório do Mar dos Açores, @rolex 

Video Narrated by Dr. Sylvia Earle, Directed by Nuno Sá @nunosaunderwater

node.text:
Today, on World Ocean Day, we celebrate Panama's commitment to a blue future with a new Hope Spot, the Coiba and Cordillera de Coiba Hope Spot! 💙🌎✨
This afternoon, Panamanian President Laurentino Cortizo and Minister of Environment Milciades Concepción signed a decree that will triple the Cordillera de Coiba marine protected area, with two-thirds designated as no-take. Panama is a Blue Leader, a country committed to achieving the protection of 30% of the global ocean by 2030, and this monumental expansion will result in Panama protecting over 30% of their territorial waters. The expansion will also connect the boundaries of Cordillera de Coiba with the Colombian Malpelo Fauna and Flora Sanctuary and Yurupari-Malpelo protected areas, a direct result of Panama and Colombia's collaborative, binational marine conservation efforts. This "new binational area" will cover more than 121,500 square kilometers (46,900 square miles) and is a major advancement in the protection of the Eastern Pacific and hopeful progress towards protecting 30% of the ocean by 2030!

Hope Spot Champion: Hector Guzman/@smithsonianpanama 
Hope Spot Partners: @divebasecoiba 

Video by @kipevansphoto & @cutcanvas, edited by @seanmolloymedia

“I want to salute Randall Arauz, his partners, and the Cocos Island Hope Spot. I wholeheartedly encourage full protection for this biologically important part of the Eastern Tropical Pacific. If we can relieve the pressure of fishing and expand the area around Cocos Island National Park, it would be a cause for hope to restore all that has been lost. The oceans are in trouble, but we have the knowledge and power to do better and protect what remains. We, humans, need a healthy planet for our own well-being and survival – and the wild animals will thank us." #SylviaEarle 

Dive into our newest Hope Spot, Cocos Island in Costa Rica, through the link our bio!

node.text:
In November 2018, the Mission Blue team and conservation partner @oceanic.society embarked to Palau, part of the Micronesian Islands Hope Spot.

In 2015, President Remengesau declared 80% of Palau's waters a marine reserve – but what about the parts that are fished? And what about the Palauans who have relied — and continue to rely — on the ocean for sustenance and income? Finally, how does one strike a balance so that all life including humans can thrive for generations?

We visited the Northern Reef Fisheries Co-Op and spoke to Bridget Adachi, Steven Victor, Masubed Tkel and Harper Skang to learn how they're working to unify local fishermen around the practice of sustainable fishing.

Video by @kipevansphoto, Brett Loveman, and @seanmolloymedia

node.text:
Palau, part of the Micronesian Islands Hope Spot, has 70 marine lakes that are scattered across its islands. One of these lakes is aptly named Jellyfish Lake, as it is home to thousands of jellyfish that spend their days traversing the lake following the path of sun while feeding on algae. Visitors can swim alongside these jellies without worry since their sting is not strong enough for people to feel. 💛 
Video by Brett Loveman and @kipevansphoto 
A wave of thanks to @actaiglobal , Glenn Bucksbaum, the Baum Foundation, @scubapro , @lightandmotiondive , and @fishnfins_palau  for making the 2019 Hope Spot Expedition to Palau possible!

Polar diving is cold enough to take your breath away - literally! After the initial shock of getting in the icy water, our dive team was treated to a beautiful underwater world. In frigid conditions, divers use plenty of specialized protective gear, including drysuits and specially gauged regulators. 
Splash in with Expedition Director @kipevansphoto from the warmth of your home - no drysuit required. 
Video by Kip Evans @kipevansphoto and Brett Loveman @cutcanvas , and edited by Sean Molloy @seanmolloymedia.

node.text:
Mission Blue Hope Spot Expeditions have visited Hope Spots around the world exploring critical ocean habitats and are designed to create awareness, foster partnerships, and build broad public support for the creation of marine protected areas across the globe. 
In 2018, with our partners @polarbearsinternational , and with support from @biotherm , we embarked on our first Hope Spot Expedition in the Arctic at Spitsbergen Island. Located in the chilly waters between mainland Norway and the North Pole, this Arctic Hope Spot supports a high diversity of marine species and contains many unique habitats found nowhere else in the world, including dramatic glaciers and mountain fjords. 
This week we will we will virtually take you back to this this special, at risk Hope Spot. 
Video by Brett Loveman @cutcanvas and Kip Evans @kipevansphoto. 
Big blue thank you to our expedition partners @biotherm @polarbearsinternational #IUCN @scubapro @gates.underwater @lightandmotiondive

In 1979, Dr. Sylvia Earle set the world record for the deepest untethered dive (a record she still holds!), which earned her the nickname "Her Deepness". Dr. Earle wore a specialized, armored JIM diving suit and descended 1250 ft (381 meters) to the ocean floor strapped to the front of a submarine. Once on the seafloor, Dr. Earle untethered herself from the vehicle and went exploring at a depth no human had done before for more than two hours!

The Quirimbas Archipelago is really a special place - a shining beacon of hope on the African coastline. Exciting news! We are teaming up with ECO Magazine to publish a special digital issue that features the most recent scientific knowledge and solutions to address one of the biggest threats to the ocean: human-made pollution. 

Available this October, the Marine Pollution digital edition will reveal the latest statistics and pollution monitoring data, explore novel detection and removal technologies, discuss environmental-friendly alternatives, and determine the infrastructure and policy changes needed to tackle the pollution crisis facing our ocean.

We're inviting our ocean community that is participating in activities in all fields related to marine pollution to submit a contribution, dive into the Ocean Story announcement to learn how! Link in bio

node.text:
We are thrilled to share that the Quirimbas Archipelago has new Hope Spot Champions, Dr. Tessa Hempson and Dr. Mark Ziembicki! Originally designated in 2013, the Quirimbas Archipelago Hope Spot includes 34 islands, as well as coastal zones on the adjacent east African mainland, and offshore habitats. The Quirimbas Archipelago boasts the region's highest biodiversity and high productivity, which supports numerous species including hawksbill and green sea turtles, giant grouper, grey reef sharks, giant trevally, the endangered Indian Ocean humpback dolphin, bumphead parrotfish, and Napoleon wrasse. The new Hope Spot Champions and their Partners are dedicated to conserving this remarkable Hope Spot, and are currently working to expand the Vamizi Marine Sanctuary, a community-driven marine protected area (MPA), for the benefit of the wildlife and local communities. 

Learn more about this Hope Spot in Ocean Stories through the link in bio!

"The Azores Archipelago is a magnet for life. It really is a magical place. Launching the Azores as Hope Spot is so logical – just ask the whales. They know how special this place is. This used to be a place where whales were killed and now people are making a living by respecting the whales and having people come out and visit them as fellow citizens of the planet." #SylviaEarle 

The Azores Archipelago was recently recognized as a Hope Spot in support of the comprehensive network of marine protected areas and collaborative efforts to manage and preserve its ecological and biological wonders. 

Splash into this Hope Spot through the link in our bio! 

Hope Spot Champions: Christopher Kim Pham with with Instituto de Investigação em Ciências do Mar Okeanos, Universidade dos Açores and Carla Damaso with OMA - Observatório do Mar dos Açores

Hope Spot Partners: @waittinstitute @oceanoazulfoundation, Azores Marine Litter Lab, Okeanos Research Centre/University of the Azores, @fabricadabaleia, OMA - Observatório do Mar dos Açores, @rolex 

Video Narrated by Dr. Sylvia Earle, Directed by Nuno Sá @nunosaunderwater
